article.description: Gabriela Marginean scored 26 points and Drexel squandered most of a 16-point second-half lead but held on Sunday, beating James Madison 64-58 in the Colonial Athletic Association tournament championship to earn its first NCAA tournament berth.
article.headline: Drexel holds on to win CAA after wasting lead over James Madison
article.linkText: Drexel claims its first NCAA tournament berth
article.story:
HARRISONBURG, Va. -- Gabriela Marginean backed up her Colonial Athletic Association player of the year award by leading her Drexel Dragons to their first NCAA tournament berth.

Marginean scored 26 points and rescued Drexel after it blew most of a 16-point second-half lead Sunday, hitting all 10 free throws in the last 96 seconds as the Dragons beat James Madison 64-58.

"I think it showed tonight why she deserved to be player of the year," guard Andrea Peterson said of her fellow senior, who edged the Dukes' Dawn Evans as the league's top player. Evans was second in the nation in scoring, with Marginean right behind her in third.

Evans also scored 26 Sunday.

Marginean actually sat for long stretches of the title game in foul trouble, but looked as calm as could be making clutch free throws that made James Madison's rally fall short.

"To my surprise, I wasn't even nervous," said Marginean, a native of Romania. "I knew how to shoot foul shots. I know I can make them, so I wasn't nervous at all."

The Dragons (24-8) were 13-for-16 from the line in the final 1:36, then celebrated at midcourt as James Madison fans head for the exits. The experience was new to them all.

"I didn't even know there was a press conference like this," Drexel senior Nicole Hester said.

Evans had 17 points in the final 4:13, but twice missed a free throw in the last 29 seconds that could have made it a one-possession game.

Jalissa Taylor added 16 points and 12 rebounds for James Madison (23-9). Coach Kenny Brooks said he felt responsible for the uphill climb his team had most of the way. The Dukes trailed 28-22 at halftime, and then let the Dragons build their lead to 16 with 11:52 left.

"They had more poise than we did," Brooks said. "I apologized to them. I felt like we were out of sorts for 90 percent of the basketball game and I couldn't reel them in."

The top-seeded Dragons ended Old Dominion's NCAA-record 17-year run as tournament champions in the semifinals Saturday. The program, started in 1982-83, has claimed just one other conference title.

"I don't think it's really sunken in yet," Peterson said. "I think when tomorrow comes and we're sitting there, that's when it will really hit us. This is a big step for us."

For a time, it looked like it would be a stroll, but then James Madison rallied behind Evans, who got hot down the stretch.

The sophomore hit three 3-pointers and twice was fouled while shooting 3s in the final minute, but each time missed the middle free throw, keeping the Dragons more than one possession ahead.

James Madison got within 4 three times in the closing minutes, but never got closer.

The Dukes came up just short on their home court, but Evans said jitters weren't the problem. She finished 7-for-20 from the field and had seven of JMU's 17 turnovers.

"We just didn't handle their pressure very well," Evans said
